about 1369","1431":"1431","about 1425":"about 1425","1386":"1386","1439":"1439","1427":"1427","England":"England","Hampshire, England":"Hampshire, England","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","Gatcombe, Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England":"Gatcombe, Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bramshot was born about 1391, in Sussex, England, his father, John Bramshott, was 63 and his mother, Elizabeth Lisle, was 47. He married Joan before November 1402, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 12 January 1431, in Gatcombe, Isle of Wight, Hampshire, England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"about 1391–12 January 1431":"umbes 1391–12. jaanuar 1431","1382–Female":"1382–Surnud","1391–1431":"1391–1431","–1439":"–1439","–Male":"Surnud","1386–1444":"1386–1444","1425–1468":"1425–1468","1427–1479":"1427–1479","1330–1412":"1330–1412","1346–1369":"1346–1369","about 1391":"umbes 1391","12 January 1431":"12. jaanuar 1431","before November 1402":"enne novembrit 1402","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1391":"1391","1425":"1425","1369":"1369","1479":"1479","1468":"1468","1412":"1412","1346":"1346","1444":"1444","about 1427":"um